                        </div>
                        <div class="post-faq-card">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">Can women use PRP for hairline thinning?</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Yes, PRP is effective for women experiencing hairline thinning or a widening part along the frontal hairline. Female pattern hair loss typically preserves the frontal hairline better than male pattern baldness, so women often respond well to PRP in this area.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="post-faq-card">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">What happens if PRP does not work for my hairline?</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">If PRP does not produce satisfactory hairline improvement after a full course of treatment, your dermatologist may recommend a hair transplant (FUE or FUT) to surgically restore the hairline. PRP can then be used post-transplant to improve graft survival and protect remaining native hair.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="post-faq-card">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">Is PRP for the hairline painful?</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The hairline area can be slightly more sensitive than the crown during PRP injections because the skin is thinner. However, a topical numbing cream or nerve block is applied before the procedure, so most patients report only mild discomfort. Any tenderness resolves within 24-48 hours.</p>
